< Review>
This station is clean and in order to get across the railroad tracks there is a pretty decent elevator to Sky walkway thing there. The things I don't like about it is that it's a little bit isolated from the main road and at night you want to be a little bit careful. The neighborhood isn't terrible though, but it's also more Industrial than anything else and that does lead to  isolation. No bathrooms here!</Review>

Taco Tuesday 99 cents

Montebello Hidden Treasure

Located across the street from Tierra Mia Coffee

< Rating>

< Review>
Convenient place to grab some food! They cook the food to order which is awesome. I ordered the Gringa and a fish taco. I always have to try out fish tacos at new places. Overall is was okay--the taste was a bit bland and it had way too much tomato, lettuce, etc crammed into the one taco so you lose the taste of the fish. The Gringa was good--simple and filling. It comes with al pastor, but you can substitute. My bf got the flaunts and wasn't a fan since they made it with corn tortillas instead of flour making it extremely crunchy. Lastly, the meat was chewy like jerky as it was overcooked. I would like to go back and try something else though, possibly the super nachos or the mulitas.<//Review>

< text>
As I would drive to work, I continually passed by this place just a few blocks away. The time had come to finally give this place a try. One drawback was the seating area, it was 4 small tables outside covered by a tarp. It was a very cold day so we pretty much had to bare the elements. We were hoping the food would make the cold sit worth it.

Unfortunately, the food was okay, but not worth it. The order was a mixture of tacos, sopes, burritos and taquitos. The meats ranged from chicken, asada, pastor and lengua. We all agreed that the food was ok but nothing stood out. Service was ok, food ok, overall an ok visit.<//text>

<Resp>None</Resp><Review>Thought I would share my experience, as it honestly wasn’t as bad as the other reviews warned. I called right when they opened to inquire about paying a visit since I’ve been having some issues that I needed addressed for my piece of mind. The nurse/medical assistant who answered the phone was very pleasant, and did forewarn me that the doctor wouldn’t arrive until after 11 am. Knowing that, I didn’t show up until after 12 just invade the doctor was late. Upon arriving, the check in process was pretty seamless. Signed a clip board, had my insurance verified, and waited about 30-45 minutes before I was called into the exam room. Again the nurse/medical assistant who did my vitals was pretty pleasant, and efficient. Only waited about 15-20 minutes before I saw the doctor. He was knowledgeable, efficient, and in my opinion had excellent bedside manner (a lot of doctors fail to have this). I went back to the front desk to get my prescription, and I was in my merry way. I would come back without hesitation, everyone has a different experience. Mine was great 🤷🏻‍♀️🙂</Review><username>Crystal Aguila< /username>< GmapID>

< text>
We have had such a hard time finding cats to live on our property. I found this organization from a random google search and it has been the best discovery. They were so thorough in understanding our needs and hopes and also so helpful in setting us up for success with our barn cats. <Response>None< /Response><Date>1622735970645< /Date>< rating>
5< /rating>
< pictures>
None</pictures>
< review>
If you are looking for a barn cat, or even a companion cat, I highly recommend LYFF.   We have adopted 4 cats over a course of a year from their barn cat program.  They delivered the cats to us, provided advice and after care (one of our cats had a runny nose and they provided antibiotics) and even provided a nice care package with the last two.

Some of the cats only spend a few days in the shelter, but one of them was about ready to be euthanized before he was brought to us.  This gives the cats a chance at the life they want to live--even though being outdoors is still a risk for them--that's where they came from originally without being spayed or neutered, or having a steady source of food and water.  Most of the cats warmed up to humans pretty quickly.  We even have one that hangs out with us all day and follows us around the ranch and sleeps on our front porch.

The interaction with the staff/volunteers at LYFF has been very positive and they really care about their cats.<//review>

The services this organization does for you are extraordinary. Super reliable, affordable and they really took care of my NOW fur babies. Trust the process and go through the application process. It’s definitely worth it ; my experience with them was very open and honest from the start and they were so nice to take us in. It took about 3-4weeks for post- surgery results and recovery. <userid>102907809009131768964<//userid>< name>
Faith E</name>
< Date>
1621670095005</Date>
< rate>
1</rate>
<review>We love fur babies and were referred to LYFF by a colleague as a great organization to adopt a kitten (or two!)

We had high hopes for adopting two seemingly bonded kitties but have been sorely disappointed by the adoption process, lack of consistent follow up and what feels like arbitrary application of implementation of unusual filtering.

For example, there is question about whether renter vs owner and if landlord approves you having pets. These are normal and customary questions. What is unusual is a seemingly rigid halt to application process to reach out to an applicant's landlord to gain 3rd party consent for having pets. As a quite seasoned and mature adult, it is unusual to have an organization seeking confirmation from a person's landlord where things like this are already stipulated, outlined, or addressed in one's lease. To me (though still invasive), a copy of lease would be better avenue as landlords aren't accustomed to 3rd parties contacting them about pet adoption for their tenants.

Nonetheless, it took two follow ups from me and a direct ask about the two kitties we were seeking to adopt before I received a reply stating that they were waiting for my landlord to reply to them and that the two kittens we'd applied for were adopted out to someone else. I understand understaffing and high volume as I work as a Manager for a major Branded hotel but to not proactively inform an applicant that the kittens they're applying for were being redirected felt like a slap and severely insensitive.

Since receiving the info that the two kittens we had applied for were adopted out to someone else, we've received zero feedback, follow up, or reply. Particularly during these times, I find it difficult to believe that our application was halted because of a landlord reply when there are many alternatives to confirming, proving pet allowance. No other cat adoption organization or humane society appears to function in this manner.

Perhaps this was a one off process for us which was quite unfortunate.

I love sharing great experiences and positive stories. This experience however has fallen harshly short in so many ways.

Hopefully others will have a better adoption journey with LYFF than we did.< /review><pics>None< /pics>< response>
None< /response>

<Text>Love Your Feral Felines is an amazing non profit that helps countless cats and kittens. They save kittens from euthanasia through their foster and adoption program and make sure they go to good indoor only homes (which is by far and wide the safest option for kitties to live long and healthy lives). And they save kitties not suitable for indoor homes by placing in “barn homes” through their barn cat program which gives feral and semi feral cats a second chance at life. They also have a low cost spay and neuter person to help get kitties fixed so that they can be more healthy overall and not contribute to the overwhelming overpopulation problem. The volunteers at LYFF work tirelessly to save as many kitties as possible and are a credit to so many sweet souls that would have otherwise never had a chance. <text>Love Your Feral Felines is a great organization very clear and transparent. All the members have been friendly and great to work with.
They are all about providing a home to cats/kittens and saving feral cats lives.
They have two programs to save lives.
-Adoption program: For social cats/kittens to find suitable indoor homes they partner with Petsmart, Vet Offices and Cat Cafe to foster adoption of cats/kittens.
-Barn Cat program (no kittens): to rescue feral non-social cats from shelters that would otherwise be euthanized (no-kill does not apply to feral cats) and provide them barn homes to foster rodent control. They train barn owners on how to successfully adapt the cats to their new environment. This is part of their TNR program as well.</text>< Pictures>

<Response>None</Response><Text>Last year, I rented Public Storage in Fountain Valley at 17300 Newhope Street Fountain Valley, CA 92708.  I had a great experience renting from that site.  I liked the  professional and courteous staff who were helpful and attentive.  My billing was correct and I was not overcharged for service.

I thought my experience would be the same here at 4501 W MacArthur Blvd Santa Ana, CA 92704, however, it was not.  Like last year, I was moving out my apartment before my apartment lease expired.  I needed to move my items into storage.

I began renting a unit here July 7, 2014.  Upon meeting Anwar, the manager, I was bombarded with a bunch of questions about what things I was going to store in there.  From my previous hassle-free experience, the other public storage location had already begun processing my "paperwork" and I was on my way to begin storing my items.  Instead, I spent time here having to explain every detail to him.  I felt like I was committing some kind of crime.  In fact, he was noisy enough to even ask me what I do for a living, as if I was going to store stolen goods.  Is this the new requirement now to rent a unit - to explain the story of my life?

Like the Fountain Valley location, I was billed for the first month's rent for July 7- August 7, 2014.  However, I have not even rented at this location for a full month, however,  today, August 2, 2014, I was billed for another month of rent.  At the Fountain Valley location, I was not billed for the second month until my first full month of rent was over.  In fact, I was able to move all my things out before the second billing was due and I was NOT overcharged for any service I had not received.

Today August 2, 2014, I have checked out with Anwar's assistant.  He did not give me a confirmation printout like the Fountain Valley location.  He said I was good to go and looked annoyed to address my concern.  I asked him when I was last billed, he said I was billed again on August 1, 2014.

When I came home and went online today, I discovered I was charged for the second month TODAY, August 2.  Anwar's assistant not only lied about my last charge for rent but charged my credit card and has not terminated my rental unit!  It states the my unit is still in service and my next billing is September 1, 2014.

I am completely dissatisfied with the service at this location.  I feel as if I have been ripped off and lied to.  Now, I will have to get a hold of Anwar when he gets back to the office sometime on a weekday this week.  I have also had problems with his other female assistant who is clueless about the keys to unlock the carts.  Why is she not given the keys to the carts?< /Text><Date>1407038095837< /Date>< name>
Hung Nguyen</name>

El Borrego de Oro offers good food and service. Its interior is very simple and yet clean, organized and well lit; very typical Mexican restaurant. We came here on a Sunday brunch. I ordered Asada Quesadilla y cafe con leche. The quesadilla was warm, soft, and tasty. Coffee☕ was surprisingly good. Prices are very affordable. Staff were competent and professional. Service was moderately fast. Overall, I had a good brunch experience.< /review>

<user>107215755159862638288</user><name>Michael Boehnlein<//name>< date>
1579824027211<//date>
< Rating>
5<//Rating>
< Text>
The Technician was very nice, and kept me completely informed throughout the process. The MRI machine they use is not the typical cylinder that feels like a coffin. Instead, it's like a top and bottom hamburger bun, and you slide into the middle. This design allowed for looking around to either side, and was much more comfortable. The machine let's you know when each scan starts so you can be aware of how many more to go until you are done.

Now, the negatives. Really, only one negative, and that's the lack of headphones/music. It's not the end of the world, but during 40 minutes in the machine would have been nicer with some relaxing tunes.<//Text>

< Review>
I've been here at least 6x. Depending on when you get there, this place can be pretty busy. You need to ensure you have all your information with you, Ins info, I.D./D.L., etc...When they're busy, I find it best to occupy myself with a book, my smartphone or whatever you want to keep you from getting upset at the staff here bc there have been times when I've watched other patients that we're taken back before me, when I was there long before them!! Trust me, I had to go & ask when I saw this happen... it's bc they actually had an appt. For some procedures, you won't need to make an appt. They have the "first come, first serve" for the walk-ins. Overall, I find that if I'm kind & patient the experience is waaayyyy better for all. Namaste 🤗<//Review>
